When NodeJS added support for ESM, they needed a way to know whether your source code was ESM or CJS.

They gave two ways to control it:

File extensions:

- .cjs = CommonJS
- .mjs = ESM
- .js = ambigous

If you use .js as your file extension, they look for the nearest parent package.json file that has a "type" field:

- "type": "commonjs" # CommonJS
- "type": "module" # ESM

If they make it to the root of your filesystem without finding this field, there are a few more heuristics, but you're likely to default to CommonJS.

With this proliferation of file extensions, they decided they don't want to do file extension guessing anymore,
so if you're using ESM or any of these file extensions, you need to be explicit now.
While they were at it, they got rid of the ability to discover index files.
This is what Typescript calls "module": "NodeNext". It's the most compatible format. I recommend we use it everywhere if possible.
